    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>All that is good forever to my brother-<lb/> in-law <persName>Itzik</persName> In the
                hope that<lb/> these lines find you in good health. I<lb/> write this to let you
                know that, God be<lb/> thanked, we are well... Moreover, I want<lb/> to let you know
                that we received your<lb/> first letter, in which you wished both of us<lb/> good
                luck, which you wrote on the <date>second of<lb/> Heshvan</date> and which reached
                us a few days<lb/> ago. Perhaps the ship which carried the letter<lb/> came under
                the embargo and <placeName>England</placeName> held<lb/> the ship back. As soon as
                transportation<lb/> was begun again, the Postmaster wrote to<lb/> me that a letter
                to my address was being<lb/> held and that as soon as I would send<lb/>
                <add>?</add> he would send the letter to me.</p>
            <p rend="Translator's note:"><persName>Leeser</persName> evidently sent money to
                his<lb/> brother-in-law, but for what purpose, it<lb/> is not clear.)</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You write that you hope I am a good<lb/> Jew. Don't doubt it You may
                be sure I</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>come of a good family, and I also<lb/> am a Schochet. To our uncle<lb/>
                <persName>Zalman</persName> we have already written...</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Your brother-in-law who calls<lb/> himself <persName role="author"
                    >Zvi ben Jacob Katz</persName>.</p>
            <p>Addressed to <addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee>, <placeName>Phila.</placeName></p>
        </body>
